title: For Sale:  LaRue Tactical SPR/M4 1.93" Mount QD LT-135
postcontent:
(Like New) I bought a scope/mount combo and do not need this mount. Mount only with 1" rings no box. The LT135 is in the same design family as our popular SPR 1.5 mount (LT104), except it is 1.93" above the rail in order to get riflescopes (like the S&B ShortDot) up above top-mounted laser/illuminators like PEQ-2's and PEQ-15's... It is as simple as that. If you do NOT need the clearance over a laser/illuminator, order the LT104. 

The LT135 places the centerline of the optic 1.93" above the top of the rail. The extended cantilever positions the scope far out front over the handguard, eliminating the need to span from the receiver to the handguard.

The popularity of the SPR series of mounts is partially due to the innovative backbone that connects the split vertical rings. This design provides a more robust platform for the optics, increases repeatability, and eliminates the need for time-consuming lapping. The rings are precision-machined with the tightest tolerances, and feature threaded steel inserts, built to withstand a lifetime of abuse.

Like all LaRue mounts, it is precision-machined out of bar-stock aluminum and Type-III hard-coat anodized. The locking LaRue Speed Levers provide outstanding return to zero; the optic can be removed, and replaced, without loss of zero. Guaranteed

postcontent:
From the best I can tell in my research, this is a Colt Police Positive Special Target Single/Double Action .22 with the "G" frame. The serial number is 7XXX and best I can tell, it was manufactured in 1911 based on the serial numbers manufactured in that time frame. This gun was manufactured from 1907 – 1925. Stamping on the top of the barrel: 

COLT’S PT. F A. MFG. CO. HARTFORD, CT U.S.A. PAT’D AUG 5, 1884 JUNE 5, 1900 JULY 4, 1905 

Stamping on left side of barrel: 

POLICE POSITVE - CAL .22 

On the left side of the frame above the grip is a symbol of an eye it seems like, with a horse rearing up in the middle with a guy riding it. 

The rear sight is missing and there is some minor wear to the finish, as well as a couple small rust spots, but overall the revolver is in great shape and mechanically sound.  

I am looking to sell for cash, or would consider a trade, or partial trade and I am willing to pay difference in cash if trading for a gun of greater value than my own, or if I accept a gun in trade that is lesser in value, I will take the difference in cash. title: For Sale:  Inland M1 Carbine 11-43, original, Excellent Condition
postcontent:
Title says it all. 11-43 barrel dated Inland Div M1 Carbine, SN 3013xxx.

It seems to be original, from what I can tell. Early Type I stock with high wood and 'I' cut for sling/oiler, all cartouches in good shape. 'RMC' in sling well, circled 'P' proof mark on bottom of pistol grip, and properly sized Ordnance Cannons in front of sling well. Handguard is Type II with 'OI' stamped on it. Safety is a plunger (type III, specificially) and the Magazine catch is unmarked, dimensions make it a type IIA. Magazine is marked 'IA', has a flat baseplate (type I), and is in great shape. A few marks on the bluing, and a few scratches, but excellent otherwise.

NO RE-IMPORT MARKS. None. Nada. Its original, and in pretty darn good shape considering. Only things that aren't 'right' is that it doesn't have a sling swivel on the (type I) barrel band and it didn't have an oiler & sling. There are a few dings in the stock and some wear on the parkerizing at a few spots on the metal, but I'd place it at about 90% overall condition.

Bluebook on a Type I Inland without rebuild puts it at $1000; an 80% gun would be $875. I'm going to shoot to the middle and ask $950 for it FTF. 

I've got a recent reproduction sling, swivel, and oiler that can go with it, if you'd like. Sling is a little thick for the oiler it came with, and I didn't want to flatten it to make it fit (like the Dutch did with the ones we gave them). I can if you'd like.

I'd prefer FTF in GSO, on a 4473, but can ship at your expense. Any questions, email me. I've got tons of photos and its parts are VERY well documented (no documentation of its military record or anything, though), so questions are welcomed.
